children.subject: Agreed this and many other classes which were horribly run had a horrible affect of my mental health due to the pandemic. To make this fair, we should be given the option to retroactively PNP any class from that semester. I did not learn anything from that class and the amount of course staff required for that class is a waste of funding (whereas other classes are forced to take on academic interns) so I am happy to hear this is finally happening but my other courses were impacted due to the workload of Sahai's EE 16b which makes PNP for all classes that semester mandatory. UCSD does this so it is fair.
<md>I agree 100%, and why are there no updates yet.  This is extremely frustrating. When should we expect a response?</md>
Same thing happened to me. It would be really helpful and fair if Fall 2021 EECS16B cohort can granted an option to switch from GRD to PNP.
*where is the post about the requirements
where is post the info about 16b requirements? just curious

Can we get an actual admin response? This is incredibly frustrating that the school put me through 30 hrs/week of nonsense and won't even acknowledge the bait and switch. There's a lot of students in my position. We deserve an answer.

That is very much a non-answer. I don't graduate until Spring 23 so the new rules apply. This does not change the fact that many were enrolled in a class against our will, based on a rationale which is just not true anymore. Turns out I never had to take 16B for a grade at all. The school is at fault, but our transcripts suffer. That is unacceptable. All I am asking for is the option to switch from GRD to PNP, a right which students are getting for the last 1.5 years of my undergrad but that I was denied based on false premises and coercion.

Looks like department chairs gave at least a partial answer @16846:

"Following long-standing campus practice, any changes to degree requirements apply to future semesters only."

history.content: No one was ever forced to enroll in EE16B; it came down to your personal choice and judgment. Many of us who were also upperclassmen decided to not enroll in EE16B last semester and this semester as we genuinely viewed the class as a significant deadweight to our intended careers. We firmly believed in the removal of such a requirement. Enrolling in such a class early on indicates that the class is at least somewhat relevant to you, and those who worked hard and achieved their desired results in that class last semester would never complain about receiving a P/NP option to cover up their grade or to wipe the course off of their transcript. It is thus reasonable that the pending decision is only effective for future semesters, and we won't be able to make accommodations for those who did not achieve a result they desired for a course taken in a past semester.

I am a 3rd year undergraduate CS major and DS minor. Last semester, I was enrolled in Sahai's 16B against my will. I was told by the administration that if I did not take the class in Fall, I would not be guaranteed admission as a Senior and therefore could jeopardize my ability to graduate on time. 16B was easily the worst 'educational' experience I have had in my 20 years on this earth, and it single-handedly tanked my GPA and will make it incredibly difficult for me to get into graduate schools.


Now I'm being told that 16B is being dropped as a requirement. I feel so betrayed by the school. You guys pointed a gun to my head and said I had to take it. That was plainly untrue. Heck, if this change occurred mid-semester in Fall, I would have gone ahead with PNP or even an INC (which is removable via petition to the Office of the Registrar), but that was not presented as a valid option at the time. I am being penalized for doing this by the book. It seems it would have been wiser for me to ignore the advice of the administration, which is just an absurd catch-22 if I've ever seen one. If the new requirements are approved, is there a mechanism in place to remove the course from my transcript?
history.subject: Petition to Remove EECS 16B From Transcript
